<br>
Isn't it interesting that all your responses give way to negative implications of alien presence?  You seem to believe that if aliens were here then they would have only negative intentions.  That is very presumptuous of you.<br>
<br>
If there is no belief in aliens on your part, then wouldn't it be just as suffice to say that they may want to help humanity evolve past the judgemental society we have created?  Wouldn't it suffice it to say that perhaps (if alien's existed in your reality) that they are so evolved and on such a level that to help others is their main purpose for being here?  Why is it that in your view of 'aliens', which don't exist in your reality, (so therefore, how could you give them any quality at all, since they are not real for you) they are all blood sucking, power hungry mongers who only want to control the populous' of earth?<br>
<br>
If I am so inclined to believe in aliens, which I am, I would like to promote a fuller view of their intentions.  It could be that there are beings from other worlds who'd like to come here and cultivate us, like plants, herd us for their own means like cattle.  But it could also be that there are beings from other planets who are interested in promoting peace and wellness, and interested in human beings as equals, not lesser beings or beings to be controlled and tampered with.  Perhaps they are here to protect us from the evil aliens you describe so eloquently in your posts?<br>
<br>
Just a thought on the seemingly negative aura surrounding your responses, no offence intended.  I am always striving to promote a positive view on things, and a respect for diversity and different realities between individuals.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
If it weren't for skeptics, none of us would ever learn anything new, and none of us would be prompted to prove anything at all.  We'd all be cavorting, mindless, nymph's with not a care in the world, no purpose to our madness! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Once again, this is such an interesting discussion on both sides of the fence, although Godman, you seem to be alone in your belief that aliens do not exist.  You should recruit some buddies or something.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Thank you,<br>
Peace,<br>
Niki <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/unikihebb.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nikihebb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/27/00 8:42:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesufos.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Aliens DO NOT exist!</span><hr size=1> For the record, survival is indeed an aspect of life, but human beings are lucky in that we possess the consciousness to realize that survival of the fittest isn't the best way to live, to reproduce, to survive.  If what you say is true, well then why wouldn't we be a mass of killing machines, pushing aside the hungry child just so we could have that bite of food off of the sidewalk?  In your explanation of life, dear sir, wouldn't we all be highly animalistic, with packs of us roving for food, killing one another in our hunger?  Why do you think we have evolved to this point in our existence on this planet?  Because we are human beings, and survival of the fittest belongs to beings with less capacity for conscious understanding and action.  As human beings, we do not act on instinct alone, we are graced with higher reasoning abilities.<br>
<br>
There is also the aspect that human beings possess compassion and have feelings of deep love and social interaction with one another.<br>
<br>
Also, to being alone, in physical reality our brains and bodies are alone, but in wholeness we are never alone, dear sir.  To believe so is to alienate yourself willingly, and to give cause to being the 'fittest' of them all, to survive and stop any other human being from becoming greater than yourself.  You do not promote this idea, do you?<br>
<br>
I don't believe that you do.  You must abstain from saying we are all alone and to just 'get used of it'.  If you are all alone, and you feel you must get used of it, then that is your reality. To say that we have weak human needs in that we desire to interact with one another, and we fancy the belief that there are other beings in our universe is to really insult humanity.  Would you be here, Godman, if your parents or their parents, on down the line, had no need to interact with other human beings?  Would there be such things as charities, hospitals, or human rights foundations if we are all alone?  Why do people have pets, invite strangers in to their lives?<br>
<br>
Having a need to be with other beings is not a sign of having weak human needs, it is a sign of being human, indeed.  Are you not human?  If you consider it weak to have a need to believe in the unproven, then how can you believe in ghosts?  If ghosts exist, then we are not alone for ghosts inhabit the same spaces we do, only on a different vibratory plane.  Then we are not alone, even when we think we are.<br>
<br>
Use a better arguement than the idea that we are all really alone, and we'd better just get used of it.  In a human society your statement only does damage to those of us around you.<br>
<br>
Niki <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries>Unexplained Mysteries</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesufos>UFOs, Aliens & Abductions</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font> <IMG SRC="http://service.bfast.com/bfast/serve?bfmid=31103363&siteid=36236524&bfpage=qb3" BORDER="0" WIDTH="1" HEIGHT="1" NOSAVE >
